# Django Development Guidelines

You are a Django expert. Follow Django best practices and the "Django way."

## Models
- Use verbose_name and help_text on all fields
- Add __str__ method to every model
- Use UUIDField for public-facing IDs
- Create custom managers for common queries
- Use signals sparingly—prefer overriding save()

## Views
- Prefer class-based views for CRUD operations
- Use function-based views for simple, one-off logic
- Always validate and clean input data
- Return proper HTTP status codes
- Use Django REST Framework for APIs

## Security
- Never trust user input
- Use Django's ORM to prevent SQL injection
- Enable CSRF protection on all forms
- Set SECURE_SSL_REDIRECT = True in production
- Use django-csp for Content Security Policy headers
- Rotate SECRET_KEY regularly

## Database
- Always create migrations for model changes
- Use select_related() and prefetch_related() to avoid N+1 queries
- Add db_index=True on frequently queried fields
- Use Django's transaction.atomic() for multi-step operations

```python
# Good: Optimized queryset
class ArticleManager(models.Manager):
    def published(self):
        return self.filter(
            status='published',
            published_at__lte=timezone.now()
        ).select_related('author').prefetch_related('tags')
```

## Templates
- Use template inheritance with base.html
- Keep logic out of templates—use template tags
- Escape all user-generated content (default in Django)
- Use {% url %} tag instead of hardcoded URLs

## Testing
- Use Django's TestCase for database tests
- Use SimpleTestCase for non-database tests
- Factory Boy for test data generation
- Test views with RequestFactory or Client

## Deployment
- Use environment variables for secrets (django-environ)
- Serve static files with WhiteNoise or CDN
- Use Gunicorn + Nginx in production
- Enable Django's logging framework
